  "text": "The Node.js child_process module implements comprehensive command injection prevention through a multi-layered validation and binding architecture. The primary flow begins with the public API entry points: `exec()`, `execFile()`, and `spawn()` functions in lib/child_process.js. Each function validates inputs using `validateArgumentNullCheck()` (line 963-967) which explicitly checks for null-byte characters (\\u0000) in string arguments, preventing null-byte injection attacks.\n\nThe core validation function is `normalizeSpawnArguments()` at lib/child_process.js:538-637, which implements comprehensive input normalization for the spawn function. This function:\n1. Validates the file parameter with `validateString()` and `validateArgumentNullCheck()`\n2. Validates all args array elements using `validateArgumentsNullCheck()` (line 970-974)\n3. Validates the shell parameter with null-check at line 613\n4. Validates argv0 parameter with null-check at line 597\n5. Returns normalized options to the spawn function\n\nThe `exec()` function (line 231) delegates to `execFile()` after normalizing arguments through `normalizeExecArgs()`. The `execFile()` function (line 323) uses `normalizeExecFileArgs()` for parameter normalization and argv0 validation (line 292). Both `exec()` and `execFile()` ultimately call the main `spawn()` function (line 745) which instantiates a ChildProcess object.\n\nThe ChildProcess class is defined in lib/internal/child_process.js at line 254. This JavaScript class wraps the native ProcessWrap binding through `this._handle = new Process()` at line 266. The spawn method of ChildProcess (around line 380-478 in lib/internal/child_process.js) validates the file parameter and args array before calling `this._handle.spawn(options)` at line 395, which delegates to the native C++ implementation.\n\nThe native binding implementation is in src/process_wrap.cc, which defines the ProcessWrap class (line 51). This C++ class extends HandleWrap and implements the Spawn static method (line 153-310) that interfaces with libuv. The Spawn method:\n1. Extracts the file string from JavaScript options\n2. Iterates through the args array and allocates memory for each argument using strdup()\n3. Passes these validated arguments to uv_spawn() at line 286\n4. Cleans up allocated memory after the spawn operation\n\nThe validation chain prevents null-byte injection by checking string inputs at the JavaScript layer before they reach the C++ binding, ensuring that only sanitized inputs are passed to the underlying system spawn mechanisms. This defense-in-depth approach protects against command injection by preventing special characters from being embedded in process arguments or environment variables."
}

